#### **Automation Workflow Architecture**

The goal of the first Zap is simple: get the URLs from all the news articles in the Google Alert (ignoring Google Alert‚Äôs unsubscribe and similar links) and save them to a Google Sheet.

I haven‚Äôt previously tried web scraping through an automation platform (Selenium \+ Python was always my gem for the job), so I‚Äôve asked ChatGPT and Claude about which web scraping platform would be best to use, and they both agreed it should be [Apify](https://apify.com/), so that was my first choice.

#### **LLM Selection: Gemini vs Other Models**

One question I got after part 1 was, ‚ÄúWhy did you pick Gemini?‚Äù And the answer comes back to the Venn diagram for the tool selection framework that I discussed last week.

Zapier allows LLMs to be used through their direct provider modules (e.g., Google AI Studio for Gemini), but you can also access most of those models through AI by Zapier, which makes the setup, testing, and model comparisons really easy. Within AI by Zapier, most models do require additional payments for the API calls, but some can be used at no additional cost, and some versions of Gemini are included in that list, so here‚Äôs the cost consideration.

Secondly, I have used Gemini models before and found them to be fairly robust and reliable, at least in comparison to other models offered for free through AI by Zapier, which covered the quality aspect for me.

I should also note here that the quality of the output (and the subsequent review time) will depend on both the model itself and the quality and clarity of the prompt, so I‚Äôd suggest spending time optimising the prompt before jumping to a different model.
